<Document>
<name>Bali Highlands — Ubud to Munduk to Lovina</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Bali Highlands — Ubud to Munduk to Lovina</h2><p><i>Bali, Indonesia · Ubud to Lovina via Kintamani, Bedugul, Munduk</i></p><p><b>Bali's cool inland — volcano crater rim, sacred lake, clove and coffee villages, the quieter north coast.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>75 km (46 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>Full day; ideally 2 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (dry); cooler year-round at altitude</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Sudden mountain rain; tight roads in Munduk; motorbikes overtaking; tourist coaches at Kintamani lookouts</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>158</td></tr></table><hr><p>Most of Bali's tourists never leave the southern beach belt. The interior is a different country — rice-terrace mountains, Hindu mountain villages where ceremonies still mark every important crossroads, and the cool (15–25 °C) high land around the central volcano group. From Ubud the road climbs to the rim of the Batur caldera at Kintamani — a 14 km-wide volcanic depression with the active Mount Batur (1,717 m) smoking inside it and Lake Batur filling its eastern half. Beyond, you cross to Lake Bratan at Bedugul (the Pura Ulun Danu Beratan temple appears to float on the water — possibly Indonesia's most photographed temple) and on to Munduk, a small clove- and coffee-growing village at 800 m with waterfalls in every direction. The descent to Lovina on the north coast is sudden — you drop 800 m in 15 km, exiting into black sand and dolphins-at-sunrise tourism.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Tegallalang rice terraces</b> — Steep terraces sculpted into a valley north of Ubud. Coffee shops on the rim. The whole landscape was choreographed by the subak system — Bali's water-sharing temple cooperation, UNESCO-listed.</li><li><b>Tirta Empul</b> — Sacred bathing temple where Balinese have come for ritual purification since 962 CE. Twelve carved spouts pour holy spring water; visitors can bathe (cover-up sarong required, sold at the entrance).</li><li><b>Penelokan / Batur</b> — Crater-rim viewpoint over Mount Batur and its lake. Sunrise hikes up Batur (start 4 AM) end with the first sun catching Mount Agung in the east. Restaurants here are tourist-priced; drive on for better food.</li><li><b>Pura Ulun Danu Beratan</b> — Lake Bratan temple complex (1633) appearing to float on the water at high water levels. Dedicated to Dewi Danu, goddess of the lakes. Pictured on the 50,000 rupiah banknote.</li><li><b>Munduk</b> — 800 m clove- and coffee-village. Munduk Waterfall (15 m, short walk in) and Banyumala twin falls are the headline; spice walks with local farmers explain the polyculture of these gardens.</li><li><b>Lovina</b> — Black-sand north coast village. Dolphins-at-sunrise boat trips (decreasingly ethical with too many boats; consider whether to participate). The reef snorkeling here is genuinely good.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
